<h1>Problem 1040 - 2017 IMOSL, G5, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Let \(ABCC_1B_1A_1\) be a convex hexagon such that \(AB=BC\), and suppose that the line segments \(AA_1, BB_1\), and \(CC_1\) have the same perpendicular bisector. Let the diagonals \(AC_1\) and \(A_1C\) meet at \(D\), and denote by \(\omega\) the circle \(ABC\). Let \(\omega\) intersect the circle \(A_1BC_1\) again at \(E \neq B\). Prove that the lines \(BB_1\) and \(DE\) intersect on \(\omega\).</p>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Get rid of points, reduce dependencies (prune). Relate pruning with forward
thinking for optimal results. Proving two lines intersect on a circle may be weird,
but remember that angle chasing often tends to save the day even in the worst of
situations.</p>
